<HEADLINE>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="4"> FT 05 OCT 94 / Maritime agency in safety plan</s>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="5"> By CHARLES BATCHELOR</s>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="6"> LONDON</s>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="7"> The International Maritime Organisation, an arm of the United Nations, yesterday announced plans to establish a panel of safety experts to recommend action following the sinking in the Baltic last Wednesday of the car ferry Estonia with the loss of more than 900 lives.</s>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="8"> The proposal by IMO's secretary-general, Mr William O'Neil, is unprecedented in the organisation's 35-year history and is intended to shorten its frequently lengthy procedures.</s>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="9"> Even so, a final decision to go ahead with the panel will not be taken until its safety committee meets in two months.</s>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="10"> The panel would be headed by Mr Giuliano Pattofatto, an Italian naval architect and chairman of the IMO's safety committee.</s>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="11"> It would consist of representatives of member governments and outside experts and would be likely to present its recommendations next May.</s>

<s docid="FT944-18204" num="12"> The UK department of transport's marine safety agency said it would ask its surveyors to check the bow doors of all ro-ro passenger ferries operating out of UK ports.</s>
</TEXT>
